  "prompt": "What is the function of centrosomes in plant cells?",
  "response": "In plant cells, centrosomes function differently compared to animal cells. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Absence in typical plant cells:\n- Most plant cells lack traditional centrosomes\n- Plant cells use alternative microtubule organizing centers (MTOCs)\n\n2. Microtubule organization:\n- Plant cells use nuclear envelope and other cellular structures to organize microtubules\n- Spindle poles are formed without typical centrosome structures\n\n3. Mitotic spindle formation:\n- During cell division, plant cells form mitotic spindles using specialized protein complexes\n- Microtubules are nucleated from the nuclear envelope and other cellular regions\n\n4. Role during cell division:\n- Organize and stabilize microtubules during mitosis and meiosis\n- Help in chromosome segregation and cell plate formation\n\n5. Differences from animal cells:\n- Animal cells have well-defined centrosomes with centrioles\n- Plant cells rely on alternative mechanisms for microtubule organization\n\n6. Specialized plant cell types:\n- Some specialized plant cells might have centrosome-like structures\n- Moss and algae species may have more recognizable centrosome-like organelles\n\nWhile plant cells lack typical centrosomes, they have evolved alternative mechanisms for effective microtubule organization and cell division.",
